WEBVTT

00:02.544 --> 00:04.046
I hate beach calls.

00:04.046 --> 00:05.506
Getting this close
to the water

00:05.506 --> 00:07.883
without being able to dive in
is torture.

00:07.883 --> 00:09.885
Not for me.

00:09.885 --> 00:11.220
It's no surprise
there.

00:11.220 --> 00:12.846
Hating one of nature's
greatest gifts

00:12.846 --> 00:14.473
is totally on‐brand
for you.

00:14.473 --> 00:17.100
I don't hate the beach.
I'm just not a fan of the ocean.

00:17.100 --> 00:18.560
You know,
psychologically speaking,

00:18.560 --> 00:20.062
fear of the water equates
to a fear

00:20.062 --> 00:22.439
of not being in complete control
of your environment.

00:22.439 --> 00:24.441
Again, on‐brand.
Uh, you know, also,

00:24.441 --> 00:26.443
good luck
dating a lifeguard.

00:26.443 --> 00:28.278
Hey, Ash.

00:28.278 --> 00:29.821
Ashley: Hey.

00:29.821 --> 00:31.448
Wow. When I called
for the cops,

00:31.448 --> 00:33.534
I didn't expect them
to send their best.

00:34.618 --> 00:36.537
And hottest.

00:36.537 --> 00:39.081
Uh,
so you called about a...

00:39.081 --> 00:41.625
Yeah.
It's right over here.

00:43.460 --> 00:45.295
Did you hear her say
"the hottest"?

00:47.256 --> 00:51.260
Washed up an hour ago.
A couple kids found it.

00:51.260 --> 00:53.095
That's why I don't swim
in the ocean.

00:53.095 --> 00:55.222
It's a dumping ground
for sewage, narcotics,

00:55.222 --> 00:57.474
and human remains.

00:57.474 --> 00:59.184
Still feel like going in?

00:59.184 --> 01:05.649
♪♪

01:05.649 --> 01:08.110
You offer French
<i>and</i> Mandarin?

01:08.110 --> 01:10.279
Chatterton: <i>Yes,</i>
<i>and you don't have to choose.</i>

01:10.279 --> 01:12.698
<i>If Jack is admitted</i>
<i>to Franklin Crest,</i>

01:12.698 --> 01:14.533
<i>he could study both.</i>

01:14.533 --> 01:15.993
He'd be three
when he starts here.

01:16.994 --> 01:18.620
This all sounds amazing.

01:18.620 --> 01:20.330
My pre‐school was
my aunt's apartment,

01:20.330 --> 01:22.958
where she watched me
and seven of my cousins.

01:22.958 --> 01:25.586
<i>That must've been so much fun.</i>
[ <i>Chuckles</i> ]

01:25.586 --> 01:29.590
<i>But study after study has shown</i>
<i>that nurturing children's minds</i>

01:29.590 --> 01:32.301
<i>between the ages</i>
<i>of three and five is crucial</i>

01:32.301 --> 01:34.678
<i>to a successful</i>
<i>academic career.</i>

01:34.678 --> 01:38.640
[ <i>Chuckles</i> ] <i>And where better to</i>
<i>nurture your child than here?</i>

01:38.640 --> 01:40.017
I can see why
they call this place

01:40.017 --> 01:41.810
the Harvard
of pre‐schools.

01:41.810 --> 01:43.353
<i>We like to think</i>
<i>of Harvard</i>

01:43.353 --> 01:45.856
<i>as the Franklin Crest</i>
<i>of universities.</i>

01:45.856 --> 01:47.482
[ <i>Chuckles</i> ]
And what do you do

01:47.482 --> 01:50.235
to keep the kids from becoming
overprivileged monsters?

01:51.528 --> 01:53.030
What are you doing?

01:53.030 --> 01:55.198
I went to schools
like this most of my life.

01:55.198 --> 01:57.326
Most of the kids were awful,
entitled.

01:57.326 --> 02:00.037
And rich and successful.
Be nice.

02:00.037 --> 02:02.914
I'm sorry. We're having trouble
with the audio on our end.

02:02.914 --> 02:04.833
We were talking
about Harvard.

02:04.833 --> 02:09.004
<i>Right. 80% of our students</i>
<i>attend Ivy League schools.</i>

02:09.004 --> 02:10.672
Oh, and that's
a selling point?

02:10.672 --> 02:12.466
The Ivy League is
a breeding ground

02:12.466 --> 02:13.508
for even more entitlement.

02:13.508 --> 02:15.385
[ <i>Chuckles</i> ]

02:15.385 --> 02:16.511
<i>I went to Harvard.</i>

02:16.511 --> 02:17.971
Well...

02:17.971 --> 02:19.139
What was ‐‐

02:19.139 --> 02:21.224
Sorry ‐‐
Frozen ‐‐

02:21.224 --> 02:24.019
You know ‐‐ call ‐‐ back.

02:25.312 --> 02:27.064
What the hell
are you doing?

02:27.064 --> 02:28.982
Look, I know you are dying
to send Jack here,

02:28.982 --> 02:30.400
but we need to make sure
it's a healthy environment.

02:30.400 --> 02:33.528
[ Cellphone chimes,
buzzes ]

02:33.528 --> 02:35.072
I have to get to work.

02:35.072 --> 02:38.200
Call them back and reschedule
the rest of the interview.

02:38.200 --> 02:40.744
Sometimes
I just can't believe you.
[ Sighs ]

02:42.287 --> 02:45.082
Hey! [ Laughs ]
Oh, congratulations!

02:45.082 --> 02:48.210
John Nolan,
Union Delegate.

02:48.210 --> 02:49.544
How do you feel?

02:49.544 --> 02:51.129
I feel amazing.
This is incredible.

02:51.129 --> 02:53.048
Guys, you didn't do this
all yourselves, did you?

02:53.048 --> 02:54.341
Oh, my goodness.
No.

02:54.341 --> 02:56.009
Uh, they were just left
at the front desk.

02:56.009 --> 02:58.720
Oh. "To LAPD's
newest union delegate.

02:58.720 --> 03:00.764
From your friends
at the mayor's office."

03:00.764 --> 03:01.765
Wow.

03:01.765 --> 03:03.725
[ Laughs ]
I am so happy for you.

03:03.725 --> 03:07.521
John, you worked
really, really hard to get this,

03:07.521 --> 03:10.273
and I think you are gonna do
just an amazing job.

03:10.273 --> 03:12.275
Thank you. That ‐‐
That actually means a lot to me.

03:12.275 --> 03:13.652
Are you okay?
Uh, yeah.

03:13.652 --> 03:17.322
Uh, it's ‐‐ it's, uh,
the pregnancy hormones.

03:17.322 --> 03:20.617
They ‐‐ They make me,
uh, pathologically cheerful.

03:20.617 --> 03:22.077
Oh.
So, um...

03:22.077 --> 03:23.995
Seriously,
it's the worst thing.

03:23.995 --> 03:26.957
Um, I am gonna go
set up the shop,

03:26.957 --> 03:29.918
and I will let you all
deal with this long line.

03:29.918 --> 03:32.379
What long line?
Oh, yes.

03:32.379 --> 03:34.423
So, in honor of your first day
as union delegate,

03:34.423 --> 03:37.384
half the cops
in the station want to, um ‐‐

03:37.384 --> 03:39.344
well, they ‐‐
they want to talk to you.

03:39.344 --> 03:40.929
Man: That's what I'm gonna talk
to him about.

03:40.929 --> 03:43.098
[ Indistinct conversation ]

03:43.098 --> 03:44.933
They haven't restocked
the vending machine

03:44.933 --> 03:46.393
with cheese puffs
in six months.

03:46.393 --> 03:47.727
I need my puffs.

03:47.727 --> 03:49.604
A citizen just filed
a complaint.

03:49.604 --> 03:50.772
I need you
to represent me.

03:50.772 --> 03:52.149
So, what was
the complaint?

03:52.149 --> 03:54.151
I was taking a statement
from a homeowner,

03:54.151 --> 03:56.153
and, well, I needed to use
her bathroom,

03:56.153 --> 03:57.654
and now she's claiming
that I destroyed her toilet.

03:57.654 --> 04:00.824
I want to use a .44 Magnum
as my duty weapon.

04:00.824 --> 04:03.368
When are we getting
air‐conditioned body armor?

04:03.368 --> 04:07.664
I'm just looking to get my
emotional support pig deputized.

04:07.664 --> 04:09.624
Seriously?

04:09.624 --> 04:11.626
You had this job
yesterday.

04:11.626 --> 04:14.337
Already cracking
under the stress, Nolan?

04:14.337 --> 04:16.173
No. I'm just wondering
what you were doing

04:16.173 --> 04:17.799
for the last 12 years
as union rep.

04:17.799 --> 04:20.135
It seems like none of these
people's needs were being met.

04:20.135 --> 04:23.472
Yeah, cops always find something
to whine about.

04:23.472 --> 04:25.348
Plus,
I told everybody

04:25.348 --> 04:27.809
how eager you are
to hear their problems.

04:27.809 --> 04:29.978
No matter how small.
You're welcome.

04:32.063 --> 04:34.357
Already hard at work,
I see.

04:34.357 --> 04:35.525
Yes, sir.

04:35.525 --> 04:37.068
Lieutenant Landon Briggs.

04:37.068 --> 04:38.361
I'm the Union ‐‐
President.

04:38.361 --> 04:40.238
Yes, I know.
Great to finally meet you.

04:40.238 --> 04:42.407
Consider this
a welcome present.

04:42.407 --> 04:45.368
But my small gift
is only the beginning.

04:45.368 --> 04:48.371
You're about to be
wined and dined
across this great city.

04:48.371 --> 04:50.582
I've already received
a‐a few gifts,

04:50.582 --> 04:52.209
but I'm just excited
to get started.

04:52.209 --> 04:53.376
I‐I'm glad you
stopped by.

04:53.376 --> 04:54.795
What's a good e‐mail
for you

04:54.795 --> 04:56.671
so I can send you a list
of my proposals?

04:56.671 --> 04:59.049
I'm sorry ‐‐ proposals?
Yeah.

04:59.049 --> 05:01.301
I, um, campaigned
on the promise of change.

05:01.301 --> 05:03.887
At the top of the list
is a mental health initiative

05:03.887 --> 05:05.972
that dispatches counselors
on all calls

05:05.972 --> 05:07.224
involving
mental illness.

05:07.224 --> 05:09.059
Oh, slow down there, son.

05:09.059 --> 05:11.853
Our fight right now isn't about
the people out there.

05:11.853 --> 05:14.397
It's about making sure
our brothers in blue

05:14.397 --> 05:17.901
get everything they deserve ‐‐
uh, paid overtime, benefits.

05:17.901 --> 05:19.694
Eh...

05:19.694 --> 05:21.279
there'll be time
for your list later.

05:21.279 --> 05:24.616
The most important thing now
is to relax.

05:24.616 --> 05:26.076
Enjoy your victory.

05:26.076 --> 05:29.079
[ Chuckles ]

05:29.079 --> 05:31.122
Hey. Heard about that hand
that washed up yesterday.

05:31.122 --> 05:33.416
God, I know.
It's super gross, right?

05:33.416 --> 05:35.377
You got any theories?

05:35.377 --> 05:37.712
A couple. I...

05:37.712 --> 05:39.881
At first, I was thinking
maybe human trafficking,

05:39.881 --> 05:41.883
maybe the boat capsized,
took someone's hand off,

05:41.883 --> 05:44.386
but then I realized that
the way the hand was severed

05:44.386 --> 05:46.555
spoke more
to some type of torture.
Ah.

05:46.555 --> 05:49.057
Sorry, I [clears throat]
watch a lot of true crime.

05:49.057 --> 05:50.058
Oh, me, too.

05:50.058 --> 05:51.434
I'm actually thinking

05:51.434 --> 05:53.770
it's a "Gone Girl" gone wrong
scenario.

05:53.770 --> 05:55.605
Ooh, I like that.

05:55.605 --> 05:58.400
Yeah, maybe she was, uh,
trying to fake a drowning,

05:58.400 --> 06:00.235
but then got caught
in her boat propeller.

06:00.235 --> 06:02.654
Exactly, yeah.
Nice.

06:02.654 --> 06:04.322
I'll see you around.
Mm‐hmm.

06:04.322 --> 06:05.657
Hey.
Hi.

06:05.657 --> 06:07.617
[ Giggles ]
What's that look?

06:07.617 --> 06:09.452
N‐Nothing.
What?

06:09.452 --> 06:10.996
You wanted to strangle that guy
last week.

06:10.996 --> 06:13.290
Now you're all
sweet on him?
"Sweet on him"?

06:13.290 --> 06:16.543
What? Did ‐‐ Did we suddenly
just get dropped in the 1950s?

06:16.543 --> 06:19.254
What?
All done.

06:19.254 --> 06:22.215
Who knew a dead hand
would require so much paperwork?

06:22.215 --> 06:24.134
Oh, hey,
do you have plans tonight?

06:24.134 --> 06:25.594
No. Why?

06:25.594 --> 06:27.929
My friend Olive won
four raffle tickets

06:27.929 --> 06:30.807
to this fancy dinner thing,
and she just invited us.

06:30.807 --> 06:32.559
What's
a "fancy dinner thing"?

06:32.559 --> 06:34.102
It's called Osia.

06:34.102 --> 06:36.396
It's an exclusive pop‐up
on the beach in Malibu ‐‐

06:36.396 --> 06:38.315
one night only,
12 fusion courses,

06:38.315 --> 06:39.774
wine pairings
included.

06:39.774 --> 06:42.193
"An experiment
in molecular gastronomy."

06:42.193 --> 06:43.820
I'll have to
think about it.

06:43.820 --> 06:46.323
What's there
to think about?

06:46.323 --> 06:47.866
Uh, the control freak
in him

06:47.866 --> 06:50.035
doesn't like to try
new things, so...

06:50.035 --> 06:51.328
I'm not
a control freak.

06:52.787 --> 06:55.832
I would be happy
to go to your dinner thing.

06:59.294 --> 07:00.337
Sergeant Grey?

07:01.463 --> 07:03.590
Lieutenant...
Caba‐relli?

07:03.590 --> 07:05.342
It's <i>Cabarelli.</i>
Ah.

07:05.342 --> 07:07.302
[ Chuckles ]
But call me Romeo.

07:07.302 --> 07:09.471
Uh, thank you.
Wade. [ Chuckles ]

07:09.471 --> 07:11.681
And how was your flight?
Eh, good, I suppose.

07:11.681 --> 07:13.350
A little tight perhaps.

07:13.350 --> 07:15.185
The <i>Carabinieri</i> does not pay
for business class.

07:15.185 --> 07:18.146
You're talking to a large man.
Trust me, I understand.
Yeah.

07:18.146 --> 07:21.358
So, you're hunting a fugitive.
Tell me about him.

07:21.358 --> 07:22.859
Kai Zullo.

07:22.859 --> 07:25.904
Murdered a woman
in a home invasion in Rome.

07:25.904 --> 07:28.698
Made off with 100,000 Euros
worth of diamonds.

07:28.698 --> 07:30.742
Landed in Los Angeles
three days ago.

07:30.742 --> 07:32.535
Does he have any family
or friends here?

07:32.535 --> 07:34.871
No. We believe he wants to hide
in a large city

07:34.871 --> 07:36.915
until he can escape
to South America.

07:36.915 --> 07:38.375
He's fluent
in many languages.

07:38.375 --> 07:40.168
Well, he came
to the right place.

07:40.168 --> 07:42.796
You can hide another city
in this city.
[ Laughs ]

07:42.796 --> 07:44.798
But the LAPD's pretty good
at finding people.

07:44.798 --> 07:46.758
Listen, I don't want to be
a burden.

07:46.758 --> 07:48.510
I'm sure
you're stretched thin.

07:48.510 --> 07:52.180
I simply need an
escorting officer with a pulse.

07:52.180 --> 07:55.141
Not to sing my own praises,
but I'm an expert lawman.

07:55.141 --> 08:00.522
Look, I have no doubt,
and I <i>am</i> stretched very thin,

08:00.522 --> 08:03.233
but it would be my honor
to work this case with you.

08:03.233 --> 08:05.568
I can't possibly ask you
to do that.

08:05.568 --> 08:07.070
I insist.

08:07.070 --> 08:09.280
I'm always looking for a way
to stretch my legs.

08:09.280 --> 08:10.740
Yeah, I do the same.
[ Chuckles ]

08:10.740 --> 08:12.617
So here's
your carry permit.

08:12.617 --> 08:16.621
And, you know,
I have a C.I. we can go see.

08:16.621 --> 08:18.581
And you can tell me more
about our suspect on the way.

08:18.581 --> 08:20.959
And when did the break‐in
take place, Mr. Swaine?

08:20.959 --> 08:23.002
Around 2:00 a. m.

08:23.002 --> 08:24.212
Okay,
what was taken?

08:24.212 --> 08:25.839
I can't say.

08:25.839 --> 08:27.382
I'm ‐‐ I'm sorry.
I don't understand.

08:27.382 --> 08:28.633
Well, if I told you,

08:28.633 --> 08:31.094
I'd be revealing ManMade Labs'
trade secrets.

08:31.094 --> 08:33.054
My company works
at the forefront

08:33.054 --> 08:35.432
of biotechnological
advancement.

08:35.432 --> 08:38.393
You're asking me to reveal
highly confidential information.

08:38.393 --> 08:40.603
Okay. Can you at least tell me
who was working at that time?

08:40.603 --> 08:42.605
I'll have to check with
the lawyers on that one.

08:42.605 --> 08:44.482
How about showing me
where the burglary happened?

08:44.482 --> 08:46.109
That way, we can have TID
dust for prints.

08:46.109 --> 08:47.652
I'm afraid
that's not possible.

08:47.652 --> 08:49.571
We have several
government clients.

08:49.571 --> 08:52.240
You don't have clearance
to go farther than the lobby.

08:52.240 --> 08:54.284
We can't do our job
without access.

08:54.284 --> 08:57.120
Oh, was I ‐‐
was I not clear?

08:57.120 --> 08:58.455
I don't expect you to.

08:58.455 --> 09:01.958
I‐I just need a case number
for insurance purposes.

09:01.958 --> 09:03.918
Sorry I'm late.
I had to yell at my husband.

09:03.918 --> 09:06.254
Detective Angela Lopez.

09:06.254 --> 09:08.590
Devon Swaine, CEO.

09:08.590 --> 09:10.592
I apologize you had to come
all the way down here.

09:10.592 --> 09:12.469
As I was telling
this officer,

09:12.469 --> 09:14.721
this matter's
extremely sensitive.

09:14.721 --> 09:17.098
We'll be handling it
in‐house.

09:17.098 --> 09:18.600
You can send over
that case number

09:18.600 --> 09:19.934
whenever you get
the chance.

09:19.934 --> 09:21.603
Thanks.

09:24.773 --> 09:26.149
[ Beeping ]

09:28.526 --> 09:30.153
How do you want to
handle this?

09:30.153 --> 09:31.988
If they don't want our help,
there's not much we can do.

09:31.988 --> 09:34.365
Just write it up
and send it over.

09:34.365 --> 09:35.950
We heard
you got a body.

09:35.950 --> 09:37.660
Yeah. He'd already lost
a lot of blood

09:37.660 --> 09:39.162
when he got here.

09:39.162 --> 09:41.331
We did everything we could,
but he bled out.

09:41.331 --> 09:44.375
[ Dramatic music plays ]

09:44.375 --> 09:47.212
Stabbing?
No.

09:49.172 --> 09:50.548
Someone cut off
his hand.

09:50.548 --> 09:53.134
♪♪

09:56.513 --> 09:58.973
How clandestine.
I could be in "Dirty Harry."

09:58.973 --> 10:01.267
[ Chuckles ]

10:01.267 --> 10:04.145
American police work.

10:04.145 --> 10:07.023
Is it really how
the movies make it look?

10:07.023 --> 10:09.192
Oh, "Dirty Harry" is
pretty outdated.

10:09.192 --> 10:12.112
But, uh...
Alright, here's my guy now.

10:12.112 --> 10:14.280
♪ <i>Perpetrate, strictly real,</i>
<i>never fake</i> ♪

10:14.280 --> 10:15.490
♪ <i>Innovate, innovate</i> ♪

10:15.490 --> 10:17.075
Flex.

10:17.075 --> 10:18.201
♪ <i>Innovate, innovate</i> ♪

10:18.201 --> 10:20.203
♪ <i>All I do is innovate</i> ♪

10:20.203 --> 10:21.830
Who's he?

10:21.830 --> 10:24.666
Romeo is an officer of
the Italian Car‐a‐binieri.

10:24.666 --> 10:25.959
<i>Carabinieri.</i>

10:25.959 --> 10:27.961
The what?
He's a cop.

10:27.961 --> 10:29.379
Just do
what he tells you.

10:29.379 --> 10:32.757
We're looking for a man
named Kai Zullo.

10:32.757 --> 10:35.593
White, six‐foot, Italian ‐‐
like me.

10:35.593 --> 10:38.179
He's in possession of stolen
jewels from my country ‐‐

10:38.179 --> 10:40.014
diamond rings, necklaces,
brooches.

10:40.014 --> 10:43.101
He's an international fugitive
wanted on a murder charge.

10:43.101 --> 10:45.603
Finding him is a big deal.

10:45.603 --> 10:48.439
[ Scoffs ]
Yeah, I'll do my best.

10:48.439 --> 10:50.108
No guarantees.

10:50.108 --> 10:52.110
♪ <i>Beg ya pardon like Dolly ♪</i>

10:52.110 --> 10:53.611
Informants.

10:53.611 --> 10:55.446
They're the same
everywhere.

10:55.446 --> 10:56.906
Even the shifty eyes.

10:56.906 --> 10:58.700
[ Engine starts ]

10:58.700 --> 10:59.826
So, what now?

10:59.826 --> 11:01.828
Let me guess.

11:01.828 --> 11:04.122
We'll "hit the streets
and see who else is talking."

11:04.122 --> 11:05.290
Not exactly.

11:05.290 --> 11:08.751
How about
"Reach for the sky"?

11:08.751 --> 11:09.752
Do you still say that?

11:09.752 --> 11:11.629
Have you seen
any cop movie

11:11.629 --> 11:13.673
that was made
in the past 40 years?

11:15.049 --> 11:16.885
Why are you wasting
my client's time, Detective?

11:16.885 --> 11:18.303
He is a busy CEO.

11:18.303 --> 11:19.679
I just have
a few questions.

11:19.679 --> 11:21.639
Which he already told you
he can't answer.

11:21.639 --> 11:23.558
Well, your client
might want to reconsider

11:23.558 --> 11:25.852
now that one of his employees
turned up dead.

11:25.852 --> 11:28.271
Who?
Mark Kilkea.

11:28.271 --> 11:30.857
Someone cut off his hand to get
past the palm scanners

11:30.857 --> 11:32.775
throughout your offices.

11:32.775 --> 11:34.986
They left him for dead,
but he somehow managed

11:34.986 --> 11:37.113
to get himself up
and stumbled into a hospital

11:37.113 --> 11:38.990
almost 24 hours later.

11:38.990 --> 11:41.117
That's horrible, but my client
has nothing to do with that.

11:41.117 --> 11:43.286
Maybe not,
but given the company's

11:43.286 --> 11:45.163
high‐tech
security protocols,

11:45.163 --> 11:46.664
there's no way
your client wasn't aware

11:46.664 --> 11:48.833
that Kilkea palmed his way
into the office

11:48.833 --> 11:50.335
right before
the robbery.

11:50.335 --> 11:51.961
But you didn't share that,
did you?

11:51.961 --> 11:54.255
In fact, according to
Mr. Kilkea's neighbors,

11:54.255 --> 11:56.257
two security officers
from your company

11:56.257 --> 11:59.052
showed up at our victim's door
right after the robbery.

11:59.052 --> 12:00.261
As you are well aware,

12:00.261 --> 12:02.347
my client's business
is highly proprietary.

12:02.347 --> 12:04.140
Yep.
I looked into that.

12:04.140 --> 12:06.768
According to your website,
the company you founded

12:06.768 --> 12:10.688
is "a pioneering force in
biotechnological engineering,

12:10.688 --> 12:13.733
making it possible
for humans to live better lives

12:13.733 --> 12:15.735
in our modern world."

12:15.735 --> 12:17.695
What are you guys making
over there?

12:17.695 --> 12:19.322
Widgets.

12:19.322 --> 12:20.990
Either you answer
my question,

12:20.990 --> 12:22.784
or we will freeze
and hold your company

12:22.784 --> 12:24.327
until we can obtain
a search warrant,

12:24.327 --> 12:26.371
and you won't sell any widgets
until I say so.

12:26.371 --> 12:28.206
Yeah, I'm not gonna
let you do that.

12:28.206 --> 12:29.332
It's a crime scene.

12:29.332 --> 12:31.209
It's my discretion
on how to process it.

12:31.209 --> 12:32.502
Let me help you out.

12:32.502 --> 12:36.798
You created the fastest,
smallest microchip in the world,

12:36.798 --> 12:38.341
and it's about to
go to market.

12:38.341 --> 12:39.550
Does that sound
about right?

12:39.550 --> 12:41.427
Where did you get that
information?

12:41.427 --> 12:44.806
Well, they just don't give
these out to anyone.

12:44.806 --> 12:46.349
What are the chips
used for?

12:46.349 --> 12:49.560
To bridge the gap between
technology and biology,

12:49.560 --> 12:51.187
and that's all
I'm going to say.

12:51.187 --> 12:53.856
And can you think of anyone
who would cut off a guy's hand

12:53.856 --> 12:55.066
to steal this tech?

12:57.318 --> 12:58.903
Chester Frey.

12:58.903 --> 13:01.030
I fired him
about six months ago

13:01.030 --> 13:03.199
for performing experiments
off‐site,

13:03.199 --> 13:05.868
doing research
my company never approved.

13:05.868 --> 13:07.161
He called me last week,

13:07.161 --> 13:09.163
insisting he was close
to a breakthrough,

13:09.163 --> 13:11.082
begged me to let him access
our lab again.

13:11.082 --> 13:13.001
I told him
to lose my number.

13:13.001 --> 13:15.628
And how dangerous would you say
Chester Frey is?

13:15.628 --> 13:18.589
He's the worst kind of crazy,
Detective.

13:18.589 --> 13:20.425
He's a zealot.

13:20.425 --> 13:21.759
So, what's next?

13:21.759 --> 13:23.177
Morning sickness,
food cravings?

13:23.177 --> 13:24.762
All of it.

13:24.762 --> 13:27.932
If it is a pregnancy
side effect, I will get it.

13:28.641 --> 13:30.643
But it's just all such
a blessing. Yeah.

13:30.643 --> 13:32.854
[ Cellphone ringing ]
Oh.

13:35.106 --> 13:36.858
John Nolan.
Gutierrez: <i>Officer Nolan.</i>

13:36.858 --> 13:38.776
<i>Elena Gutierrez,</i>
<i>district councilwoman.</i>

13:38.776 --> 13:40.903
<i>I wanted to convey</i>
<i>my personal congratulations</i>

13:40.903 --> 13:43.072
<i>on your victory.</i>
Thank you very much, ma'am.

13:43.072 --> 13:44.824
<i>We're a big fan</i>
<i>of the LAPD over here,</i>

13:44.824 --> 13:46.617
<i>so if you ever want to chat,</i>
<i>I'm around.</i>

13:46.617 --> 13:48.453
Well,
are you free tonight?

13:48.453 --> 13:51.080
I do have a couple of ideas
I've been kicking around.

13:51.080 --> 13:52.790
<i>Actually, I have a meeting</i>

13:52.790 --> 13:54.792
<i>down the street from</i>
<i>your station this evening.</i>

13:54.792 --> 13:57.086
<i>I can swing by after,</i>
<i>around 7:30?</i>

13:57.086 --> 13:59.047
That is perfect.
Thank you very much.

13:59.047 --> 14:00.339
I am looking forward.

14:00.339 --> 14:02.467
<i>Me, too.</i>

14:02.467 --> 14:05.136
Wow. Okay.
See, this is why I ran.

14:05.136 --> 14:07.305
A chance to talk
about real issues.

14:07.305 --> 14:09.057
Lopez:
<i>7‐Adam‐15, this is Lopez.</i>

14:09.057 --> 14:11.726
<i>I have an ID on our hand‐thief</i>
<i>murder suspect.</i>

14:11.726 --> 14:13.311
<i>Chester Frey.</i>

14:13.311 --> 14:14.771
<i>His house is five blocks</i>
<i>from your location.</i>

14:14.771 --> 14:16.439
<i>Sending the address</i>
<i>to your box</i>

14:16.439 --> 14:18.191
<i>and additional units</i>
<i>to back you up.</i>

14:18.191 --> 14:19.525
Copy that.
We are on our way.

14:19.525 --> 14:22.445
And thank you so much
for calling.

14:24.572 --> 14:26.324
I know. It's ‐‐
It's freaking me out, too.

14:26.324 --> 14:28.326
[ Dramatic music plays ]

14:28.326 --> 14:29.952
Police!

14:30.912 --> 14:33.122
Harper: God,
it's like a freezer in here.

14:33.122 --> 14:37.418
♪♪

14:37.418 --> 14:39.128
Chester?

14:39.128 --> 14:41.464
Come on up now.
Show me your hands.

14:41.464 --> 14:50.681
♪♪

14:50.681 --> 14:52.642
Clear upstairs.

14:52.642 --> 14:59.440
♪♪

14:59.440 --> 15:01.025
Clear.

15:01.025 --> 15:04.821
[ Tapping ]

15:06.656 --> 15:09.075
This place...

15:09.075 --> 15:10.618
Do you hear that?

15:13.704 --> 15:15.164
Police!

15:15.164 --> 15:18.042
[ Tapping continues ]

15:26.676 --> 15:27.885
Um, Nolan...

15:27.885 --> 15:35.309
♪♪

15:38.813 --> 15:41.274
Nolan: And here we have
a severed arm,

15:41.274 --> 15:42.817
moving all on its own.

15:42.817 --> 15:44.485
[ Exhales sharply ]
Uh...

15:44.485 --> 15:46.237
I can't stop staring.

15:46.237 --> 15:47.947
I think it's amazing.

15:47.947 --> 15:50.533
I mean, the human body ‐‐

15:50.533 --> 15:54.036
this truly is a miracle.

15:54.036 --> 15:55.246
Is she okay?

15:55.246 --> 15:56.789
Pregnancy hormones.

15:56.789 --> 15:59.333
Cool. Any sign
of our Dr. Frankenstein?

15:59.333 --> 16:00.960
No. He left plenty
of evidence behind ‐‐

16:00.960 --> 16:02.628
notebooks, computers.

16:02.628 --> 16:04.714
Hopefully, we can learn
what scientific breakthrough

16:04.714 --> 16:06.215
he thinks
he's so close to.

16:06.215 --> 16:08.217
Yeah, and where
to look for him next.

16:09.719 --> 16:11.762
Be right back.
Yeah.

16:14.098 --> 16:16.017
Any sign of Chester?
No.

16:16.017 --> 16:19.312
So, Chester cut off
Mark Kilkea's hand,

16:19.312 --> 16:21.189
and now there's a severed arm
in his house.

16:21.189 --> 16:23.232
That's two victims.
Afraid there's more.

16:23.232 --> 16:25.860
Harper and Nolan found a freezer
with eight more arms inside.

16:25.860 --> 16:29.071
So, is that four more victims,
or eight?

16:29.071 --> 16:31.574
Six, I think.
Four right, two left.

16:31.574 --> 16:33.034
On the initial exam,
the ME thinks

16:33.034 --> 16:34.327
they were removed
post‐mortem.

16:34.327 --> 16:37.246
Two of them had clear signs
of decomposition.

16:37.246 --> 16:39.332
So what?
He's a grave robber?

16:39.332 --> 16:40.708
We don't know yet.

16:40.708 --> 16:42.126
Well, tell TID
to get a rush on the prints.

16:42.126 --> 16:43.544
If we can get hits
on his victims,

16:43.544 --> 16:45.296
it might tell us
where he got the limbs from

16:45.296 --> 16:47.298
and who he targets.
On it.

16:47.298 --> 16:49.258
Karga:
Detective Lopez.

16:51.719 --> 16:53.804
What do you want,
Mr. Karga?

16:53.804 --> 16:56.224
Access to
Chester Frey's house.

16:56.224 --> 16:58.476
He stole proprietary property
from my client,

16:58.476 --> 17:00.645
and I need to retrieve it.
That would be a no.

17:00.645 --> 17:01.896
This is
an active crime scene ‐‐

17:01.896 --> 17:03.272
I don't think
you understand.

17:03.272 --> 17:05.274
If my client's technology
is leaked,

17:05.274 --> 17:08.945
it will destroy
a billion dollars' worth of R&D.

17:08.945 --> 17:12.198
And the LAPD isn't exactly known
for its discretion,

17:12.198 --> 17:14.617
which is why we prefer
to handle everything in‐house.

17:14.617 --> 17:17.620
Look, I get it.
But I can't help you.

17:17.620 --> 17:20.790
We're seizing everything
inside this house, Mr. Karga,

17:20.790 --> 17:24.210
and if you even attempt to step
foot inside this perimeter,

17:24.210 --> 17:26.545
you'll spend tonight
inside a jail cell.

17:28.089 --> 17:29.882
Wouldn't want to dirty
that nice suit, would you?

17:31.717 --> 17:34.095
And I would love to get
a look at Chester's computer

17:34.095 --> 17:35.763
after TID is done
processing it ‐‐

17:35.763 --> 17:37.598
you know, try to get
into his head.

17:37.598 --> 17:39.100
You think Lopez
would let me?

17:39.100 --> 17:40.268
Doesn't hurt to ask.

17:40.268 --> 17:42.603
[ Cellphone ringing ]
It's Ash.

17:42.603 --> 17:44.605
Hey, Ash.
Hey.

17:44.605 --> 17:46.482
Olive just pulled out
of the dinner thing,

17:46.482 --> 17:48.985
so now I have
all four tickets.

17:48.985 --> 17:51.779
<i>I was thinking of asking Byron</i>
<i>and his girlfriend...</i>

17:51.779 --> 17:53.823
Yeah, uh, no.

17:53.823 --> 17:55.324
Y‐You know what?

17:55.324 --> 17:57.326
Lucy's been pining after
that place all day.

17:57.326 --> 17:58.661
[ Gasps ]
Maybe we ask her.

17:58.661 --> 18:00.830
Osia? Yes. Oh, my gosh.
Yes, please.

18:00.830 --> 18:02.748
<i>Cool. Does she have</i>
<i>a date to bring?</i>

18:03.583 --> 18:05.293
Hey, Sanford.
What?

18:05.293 --> 18:06.919
You got plans tonight?

18:06.919 --> 18:08.254
What are you doing?

18:08.254 --> 18:09.964
Lucy needs a date
to a fancy dinner.

18:09.964 --> 18:11.591
Uh...

18:11.591 --> 18:14.385
[ Stammers ]
It'll be fun.

18:14.385 --> 18:16.637
Okay. Yeah.
I'm in.

18:16.637 --> 18:18.973
Uh, text me the address.

18:18.973 --> 18:20.433
She's good.

18:20.433 --> 18:21.434
Okay.

18:21.434 --> 18:23.978
♪♪

18:23.978 --> 18:25.479
What?

18:25.479 --> 18:26.731
Don't be
such a control freak.

18:26.731 --> 18:29.358
Sgt. Grey: Hey, we gave it
our best shot.

18:29.358 --> 18:31.986
Tomorrow's another day.
It always is.

18:31.986 --> 18:35.489
You know, the architecture
in this city is ghastly.

18:35.489 --> 18:38.701
Do not bad‐mouth
my city, Romeo.

18:38.701 --> 18:41.495
Oooh. So sensitive.
[ Laughs ]

18:41.495 --> 18:43.039
But I will prove it
to you.
Uh...

18:43.039 --> 18:44.373
Come to Rome.

18:44.373 --> 18:45.833
You walk down the streets,

18:45.833 --> 18:47.835
you'll see thousands of years
of history.

18:47.835 --> 18:50.296
That's what a real city
should look like.

18:50.296 --> 18:52.465
I'm serious.
Bring that wife of yours.

18:52.465 --> 18:56.510
Luna has been on me
about traveling more.

18:56.510 --> 18:59.138
Then it's decided.
You will be my guest.

18:59.138 --> 19:00.723
I will open
my doors for you.

19:01.932 --> 19:03.351
That's very generous.
Thank you.

19:05.353 --> 19:08.731
You know, you remind me
of someone I used to know.

19:08.731 --> 19:10.733
A lieutenant.

19:10.733 --> 19:12.526
His name was Santo.

19:13.861 --> 19:16.906
I was only his cadet
when I joined the <i>Carabinieri,</i>

19:16.906 --> 19:18.866
but he took me
under his wings.

19:18.866 --> 19:21.160
He showed me
my city through new eyes.

19:21.160 --> 19:23.079
Like you are now.

19:24.038 --> 19:25.748
"Used to know."

19:25.748 --> 19:27.083
What happened?

19:27.083 --> 19:29.502
My second year,
he, uh ‐‐

19:29.502 --> 19:31.379
he was shot.

19:31.379 --> 19:33.714
I was there.

19:33.714 --> 19:35.966
He died in my arms.

19:35.966 --> 19:39.887
Every day, in here...

19:39.887 --> 19:41.472
I see it.

19:43.974 --> 19:46.602
Yeah, I know a little something
about that.

19:46.602 --> 19:50.606
This is a miserable job
sometimes.

19:50.606 --> 19:52.274
That it is.

19:54.443 --> 19:57.446
And sometimes,
the best.

19:58.823 --> 20:00.366
That is true.

20:00.366 --> 20:02.702
[ Cellphone chimes, buzzes ]

20:02.702 --> 20:04.870
What's this?

20:04.870 --> 20:07.665
Ah.
Flex just got word.

20:07.665 --> 20:10.084
Kai's meeting the diamond broker
tonight ‐‐

20:10.084 --> 20:12.420
Gardner and Beverly.

20:12.420 --> 20:14.588
That is wonderful.

20:14.588 --> 20:17.091
But I don't want to keep you
from the end of your shift.

20:17.091 --> 20:19.552
Why don't you drop me off?
I'll go stake it out.

20:19.552 --> 20:21.762
If he's there,
I'll call for backup.

20:21.762 --> 20:23.180
See, I can't
let you do that.

20:23.180 --> 20:25.182
Besides, I already told
the station

20:25.182 --> 20:28.185
that I'm extending my shift
tonight, so...

20:28.185 --> 20:31.063
You've already put in so much
time on my case.

20:31.063 --> 20:33.566
Go home to your wife.

20:33.566 --> 20:38.654
You know...Luna has
book club tonight.

20:38.654 --> 20:40.448
I'm all yours.
[ Chuckles ]

20:40.448 --> 20:42.199
[ Chuckles ]

20:42.199 --> 20:44.577
Chris:
I told a foodie friend I was
coming here, and they flipped.

20:44.577 --> 20:46.787
And they said it sold out in,
like, 30 seconds.

20:46.787 --> 20:48.414
How the hell
did you get tickets?

20:48.414 --> 20:50.666
My friend won them
in a raffle.

20:50.666 --> 20:53.127
I'm sorry, but who puts
a restaurant on the beach?

20:53.127 --> 20:55.463
I mean, you're just asking for
sand in your food.

20:55.463 --> 20:56.964
I don't get it.

20:56.964 --> 20:59.425
Hostess: For your first course,
we have Chef Celine Barris' take

20:59.425 --> 21:01.594
on blinis and caviar ‐‐

21:01.594 --> 21:04.430
a savory enoki pancake
with fruit of the forest roe,

21:04.430 --> 21:07.600
and smoked Himalayan salt
espuma.

21:07.600 --> 21:08.934
Enjoy.

21:11.437 --> 21:14.106
Was any of that English?
Let me translate.

21:14.106 --> 21:15.191
All you need to know

21:15.191 --> 21:16.692
is that that pancake
is made of mushroom,

21:16.692 --> 21:18.110
which I know is not
your favorite, so I'm just ‐‐

21:18.110 --> 21:20.863
Ooh, no, take it.
Yeah.
Yeah.

21:20.863 --> 21:23.115
I'm sorry. I didn't know
you don't like mushrooms.

21:23.115 --> 21:24.658
Oh, it's okay.

21:24.658 --> 21:26.786
I'm not the most adventurous
eater, either.

21:26.786 --> 21:29.121
But once on vacation in Jamaica,
I did have curry goat.

21:29.121 --> 21:31.624
Ooh.
Was his name Gerald?

21:31.624 --> 21:34.752
God, shut up.
[ Laughing ] Don't.

21:34.752 --> 21:35.753
It's nothing.

21:35.753 --> 21:37.046
No, it's something.

21:38.339 --> 21:40.466
Okay, we had
a 2‐11 at a petting zoo.

21:40.466 --> 21:42.134
All of the animals
got loose.

21:42.134 --> 21:43.677
So, we ‐‐
we nab our suspect,

21:43.677 --> 21:45.346
we him back to the shop,
and that's where we find ‐‐

21:45.346 --> 21:47.848
Gerald the goat.
He is so cute.

21:47.848 --> 21:49.558
And he's sitting
in Lucy's seat.

21:49.558 --> 21:51.644
Well, because I forgot
that I had rolled down
the ‐‐ the window.

21:51.644 --> 21:53.354
You know,
who knew goats could jump?

21:53.354 --> 21:55.481
Look, she tries to talk
him out of the shop,
but it's a goat, right?

21:55.481 --> 21:57.525
So, she spends five minutes
making goat noises

21:57.525 --> 21:59.401
at this thing.
[ Laughs ]

21:59.401 --> 22:01.821
Yes, he called me
"goat whisperer" for
all of last February.

22:01.821 --> 22:03.906
It was great.
The darn thing never moved.

22:03.906 --> 22:06.367
Oh, you know, we finally had
to call animal control.

22:06.367 --> 22:08.661
[ Chuckles ]
[ Laughs ]

22:08.661 --> 22:10.913
It's funny.

22:13.707 --> 22:16.126
Nolan: Thank you so much
for coming, Councilwoman.

22:16.126 --> 22:18.170
Of course.
It is my pleasure.

22:18.170 --> 22:19.964
You know, every time
that I've reached out

22:19.964 --> 22:22.550
to one of my district's
union delegates,

22:22.550 --> 22:24.635
they always brush aside
my invitations to talk.

22:24.635 --> 22:27.012
So imagine my surprise
when you actually seemed excited

22:27.012 --> 22:28.681
to talk to me.
Oh, I am.

22:28.681 --> 22:30.850
No, I‐I campaigned
on the promise of change,

22:30.850 --> 22:32.810
and I meant it.

22:32.810 --> 22:35.521
Some of the best people
you could ever meet

22:35.521 --> 22:36.939
are in the LAPD.

22:36.939 --> 22:38.941
I would like the institution
to reflect that.

22:38.941 --> 22:40.192
How can I help?

22:40.192 --> 22:41.944
I'll be honest,
Councilwoman ‐‐

22:41.944 --> 22:43.237
Elena.
Elena.

22:43.237 --> 22:45.197
Math was never
my strong suit.

22:45.197 --> 22:47.241
My brain bleeds
just looking at my taxes.

22:47.241 --> 22:49.410
But I was going over
our departmental budget,

22:49.410 --> 22:52.079
and even I can see
we're putting a lot of money

22:52.079 --> 22:53.622
in the wrong places.

22:53.622 --> 22:55.082
You won't get an argument
from me.

22:55.082 --> 22:57.501
Now, at least 20%
of our service calls

22:57.501 --> 23:00.254
are for mental health
or substance‐use issues.

23:00.254 --> 23:02.756
Now, these people
don't need to be policed.

23:02.756 --> 23:04.508
They need
crisis intervention

23:04.508 --> 23:06.886
and a counselor
dispatched to the scene.

23:06.886 --> 23:08.929
I've been thinking about
a pilot program.

23:08.929 --> 23:11.015
If you could help me get
an audience with the mayor ‐‐

23:11.015 --> 23:12.725
I'm so sorry.
This is ‐‐ It's my first day.

23:12.725 --> 23:15.060
I'm already overstepping.
No.

23:15.060 --> 23:16.937
Do not apologize.

23:16.937 --> 23:19.732
Your empathy is ‐‐
it's genuine. I can tell.

23:19.732 --> 23:21.317
Tell me more
about this program, please.

23:21.317 --> 23:22.484
Alright.

23:22.484 --> 23:24.320
Well, people don't like
the idea of experimenting

23:24.320 --> 23:25.988
on the dead
for emotional reasons,

23:25.988 --> 23:28.198
but it's an important tool
in the medical field.

23:28.198 --> 23:30.075
Yeah,
I'm not arguing that.

23:30.075 --> 23:31.827
All I'm saying is that
turning people into cyborgs

23:31.827 --> 23:33.203
is how the world
is going to end.

23:33.203 --> 23:35.664
So, then, I guess you
haven't volunteered

23:35.664 --> 23:37.166
to be an organ donor
when you die?

23:37.166 --> 23:38.792
Tim? No.

23:38.792 --> 23:41.128
He wants to be cremated
and spread over Dodger Field.

23:41.128 --> 23:43.714
I was joking
when I said that.
[ Chuckles ]

23:43.714 --> 23:45.966
My ashes would screw up
the pH level of the grass.

23:45.966 --> 23:48.135
I can't believe you actually
called and asked.

23:48.135 --> 23:51.388
I like the Dodgers.
Yeah.

23:51.388 --> 23:53.098
And for dessert,

23:53.098 --> 23:55.935
we have a spherical
coconut‐mango emulsion

23:55.935 --> 23:58.604
with a dusting
of jalapeño essence.

23:58.604 --> 23:59.897
Enjoy.

24:01.440 --> 24:02.858
This is a joke, right?
[ Chuckles ]

24:02.858 --> 24:06.654
I mean, people don't actually
enjoy eating this food, do they?

24:08.864 --> 24:10.366
I'm sorry.
I‐I didn't mean to ‐‐

24:10.366 --> 24:12.242
Excuse me.
I need to use the restroom.

24:13.953 --> 24:14.954
Whoa.

24:14.954 --> 24:16.872
[ Siren wailing in distance ]

24:16.872 --> 24:18.207
Wade, please.

24:18.207 --> 24:20.334
I feel bad,
making you waste your night

24:20.334 --> 24:22.294
for what's likely
a goose chase.

24:22.294 --> 24:23.796
This is my case.

24:23.796 --> 24:26.674
I'll take the burden
for the both of us.

24:26.674 --> 24:28.842
I'm starting to feel like you're
trying to get rid of me.

24:28.842 --> 24:32.680
No. [ Chuckles ]
I'm loving our time together.

24:32.680 --> 24:36.767
It's just that...it's not good
to work all the time.

24:36.767 --> 24:38.686
You need to
enjoy life more.

24:39.937 --> 24:42.398
That's one thing I've learned
after Santo died.

24:45.609 --> 24:48.028
There he is.
I'll call for backup.

24:48.028 --> 24:49.405
Hey!

24:49.405 --> 24:54.159
♪♪

24:54.159 --> 24:56.245
<i>Preso, bastardo!</i>

24:56.245 --> 24:59.248
[ Gunshots ]

24:59.248 --> 25:06.213
♪♪

25:06.213 --> 25:07.631
[ Speaking Italian ]

25:07.631 --> 25:09.383
Sgt. Grey:
7‐Adam‐100, shots fired.

25:09.383 --> 25:11.385
Officer needs help.

25:11.385 --> 25:15.055
Suspect is white male,
black jacket, black pants.

25:15.055 --> 25:17.057
Hey.
What the hell was that?

25:17.057 --> 25:18.892
He had a gun.
You did not see?

25:18.892 --> 25:20.227
No, I didn't see.

25:20.227 --> 25:22.354
Well, he did.
He's a very dangerous man.

25:22.354 --> 25:23.981
If I'd hesitated,
he would have killed me.

25:28.777 --> 25:31.071
[ Drawers clattering ]

25:31.071 --> 25:32.865
[ Sighs ]

25:32.865 --> 25:34.408
Yeah.

25:34.408 --> 25:36.118
Good morning.

25:36.118 --> 25:37.870
Franklin Crest e‐mailed.

25:37.870 --> 25:42.082
Their enrollment is suddenly
full for two years from now.

25:42.082 --> 25:44.418
Okay, I'm sorry,
but if they are that sensitive

25:44.418 --> 25:45.794
to questions about
their students,

25:45.794 --> 25:47.588
then maybe we shouldn't
send Jack there.

25:47.588 --> 25:49.214
We should send him
to public school.

25:49.214 --> 25:51.675
Says the rich boy
who's never been to one.

25:51.675 --> 25:53.969
Well, you went to
public school.

25:53.969 --> 25:55.471
You turned out great.

25:55.471 --> 25:56.972
You're doing it again.

25:56.972 --> 25:58.766
Wait, doing what?

25:58.766 --> 26:00.768
Shoving your privilege
into your back pocket

26:00.768 --> 26:02.936
when you can actually use it
for something good,

26:02.936 --> 26:05.022
like the education
of our child.

26:05.022 --> 26:06.982
That's not fair.
But it's accurate.

26:08.609 --> 26:10.819
Look, public school
can be wonderful.

26:10.819 --> 26:13.906
Then what's the problem?
You took away our options.

26:13.906 --> 26:16.158
Even if Jack got into
Franklin Crest,

26:16.158 --> 26:19.328
we might not have enrolled him,
but you sabotaged it

26:19.328 --> 26:21.371
and essentially made
a decision without me.

26:21.371 --> 26:22.706
And why did you do it?

26:22.706 --> 26:24.833
Because you have
private school baggage.

26:26.835 --> 26:29.004
Okay. Fine.

26:30.297 --> 26:33.300
Maybe I do have
some...baggage.

26:33.300 --> 26:35.344
Maybe I'm afraid that
our son will become

26:35.344 --> 26:38.889
the same poster boy
for entitlement that I was,

26:38.889 --> 26:42.559
until I realized
I didn't like myself,

26:42.559 --> 26:44.978
and I set out to become
the man that you love.

26:44.978 --> 26:47.356
Mostly.

26:47.356 --> 26:49.733
I'm just disappointed
that you didn't have more faith

26:49.733 --> 26:51.610
in us as parents.

26:57.908 --> 27:01.203
<i>They will record</i>
<i>my name in history.</i>

27:01.203 --> 27:03.038
<i>They will parade me through ‐‐</i>

27:03.038 --> 27:05.457
Hey.
You're here early.

27:05.457 --> 27:07.000
Yeah.
I couldn't sleep.

27:07.000 --> 27:09.086
All I could think of
was this disembodied hand

27:09.086 --> 27:11.713
climbing into my bed,
so I've been here,

27:11.713 --> 27:14.091
scrubbing through
Chester's video journals.

27:14.091 --> 27:15.509
You come
to any conclusions?

27:15.509 --> 27:17.386
I try not to use the word
"crazy"...

27:17.386 --> 27:20.347
He cut off a guy's hand and
reanimated a woman's dead arm.

27:20.347 --> 27:22.683
He's crazy.
Yeah.

27:22.683 --> 27:25.227
Okay, so,
he shot this next video

27:25.227 --> 27:27.688
the day before he cut off
Mark Kilkea's hand

27:27.688 --> 27:29.731
and used it
to break into ManMade Labs.

27:31.066 --> 27:34.653
<i>I am here,</i>
<i>trying to officiate a marriage</i>

27:34.653 --> 27:38.824
<i>between science and humanity,</i>
<i>and nothing's working.</i>

27:38.824 --> 27:40.409
<i>I know what I have to do.</i>

27:40.409 --> 27:42.077
<i>I've never wanted</i>
<i>to resort to violence,</i>

27:42.077 --> 27:44.955
<i>but this is not the time</i>
<i>to be faint of heart.</i>

27:44.955 --> 27:48.750
<i>I am so close.</i>
<i>I am so close!</i>

27:48.750 --> 27:50.878
<i>I will show them my miracles,</i>

27:50.878 --> 27:53.213
<i>then my sins will be forgiven</i>
<i>forever.</i>

27:53.213 --> 27:56.049
[ Key clacks ]
Okay, so, this next one

27:56.049 --> 27:59.970
is his last video entry,
and it was shot yesterday.

27:59.970 --> 28:02.306
<i>It worked.</i>
[ <i>Breathing heavily</i> ]

28:02.306 --> 28:05.309
<i>Hear that? Hear it?</i>
<i>Hear it?</i>

28:05.309 --> 28:08.979
[ <i>Tapping</i> ]

28:08.979 --> 28:10.939
<i>The wrist is contracting.</i>
<i>The ‐‐ The ‐‐</i>

28:10.939 --> 28:13.150
<i>The hand is knocking,</i>

28:13.150 --> 28:16.695
<i>pounding on the doors</i>
<i>of immortality!</i>

28:16.695 --> 28:18.655
<i>This changes everything.</i>

28:18.655 --> 28:20.282
<i>Who needs a prosthetic limb</i>
<i>when you can be made whole</i>

28:20.282 --> 28:22.451
<i>with a reanimated one?</i>

28:22.451 --> 28:24.953
<i>I'm creating life.</i>

28:24.953 --> 28:26.538
<i>I am a god.</i>

28:26.538 --> 28:27.789
<i>Whoo‐‐</i>
[ Key clacks ]

28:27.789 --> 28:29.291
Anything in these videos
that can lead us

28:29.291 --> 28:30.876
to where he's hiding?
Not that I've seen.

28:30.876 --> 28:32.210
Well,
let's keep looking.

28:32.210 --> 28:34.588
What do you need?
Close the door.

28:34.588 --> 28:36.006
Come here.

28:36.006 --> 28:37.799
I heard you were involved
in a shooting. You alright?

28:37.799 --> 28:39.676
That was
my Italian counterpart.

28:39.676 --> 28:44.264
He and I tracked down
his fugitive ‐‐ Kai Zullo.

28:44.264 --> 28:46.016
But the second
Romeo saw the guy,

28:46.016 --> 28:48.101
he opened fire,
claimed he saw a gun.

28:48.101 --> 28:49.394
But you didn't.
Correct.

28:49.394 --> 28:50.646
Did you check
your body cam?

28:50.646 --> 28:52.648
Of course,
but there wasn't a good look.

28:52.648 --> 28:54.191
I phoned Italy
last night.

28:54.191 --> 28:56.151
Spoke to one of
their inspectors.

28:56.151 --> 28:59.363
She told me that Romeo is
currently under investigation

28:59.363 --> 29:01.156
for misconduct.

29:01.156 --> 29:03.241
So he's a dirty cop?
Seemingly.

29:03.241 --> 29:06.119
I think it's prudent that
we find Kai before Romeo does.

29:06.119 --> 29:07.913
Okay, so what do we know
about Kai so far?

29:07.913 --> 29:09.915
He's in
a foreign country.

29:09.915 --> 29:11.875
He appears not to have friends
or family here.

29:11.875 --> 29:13.168
He has to stay under
the radar,

29:13.168 --> 29:15.504
so he can't use a credit card
or his ID.

29:15.504 --> 29:17.547
Right, but he is gonna need
a place to stay.

29:17.547 --> 29:19.591
A no‐tell motel
that accepts cash.

29:19.591 --> 29:21.009
We will
start canvassing.

29:21.009 --> 29:23.804
Thanks. I'll keep Romeo busy
while you look.

29:23.804 --> 29:25.222
Hey.
<i>Implant the size of ‐‐</i>

29:25.222 --> 29:27.307
We got hits on prints
on three of the arms

29:27.307 --> 29:28.892
found in Chester's place.

29:28.892 --> 29:30.852
All three were from unclaimed
or indigent people

29:30.852 --> 29:33.563
whose bodies had been in storage
in the County Morgue.

29:33.563 --> 29:36.066
That's a great way to grab
bodies no one would ever miss.

29:36.066 --> 29:38.443
The County holds onto the
remains of unclaimed individuals

29:38.443 --> 29:39.820
for up to three years,

29:39.820 --> 29:41.571
then they're buried
in a pauper's grave.

29:41.571 --> 29:43.031
That's sad.

29:43.031 --> 29:45.617
D‐Does Chester have a connection
to the morgue?

29:45.617 --> 29:47.619
Not that we know of,
but it's possible

29:47.619 --> 29:50.372
that he found an
employee who was willing
to sell him body parts.

29:50.372 --> 29:52.708
We'll check it out.
Yeah.

29:52.708 --> 29:54.251
[ Elevator bell dings ]

30:01.049 --> 30:03.885
[ Suspenseful music plays ]

30:03.885 --> 30:06.179
Police.
Anyone here?

30:06.179 --> 30:10.350
♪♪

30:10.350 --> 30:12.477
He's here.

30:16.356 --> 30:17.941
It's still wet.
Control, 7‐Adam‐100.

30:17.941 --> 30:19.693
Can I get backup
for a 415?

30:19.693 --> 30:21.737
Male, unknown weapon.
Standby for further.

30:21.737 --> 30:24.364
♪♪

30:24.364 --> 30:32.748
♪♪

30:32.748 --> 30:36.501
♪♪

30:36.501 --> 30:39.296
♪♪

30:39.296 --> 30:44.551
♪♪

30:44.551 --> 30:49.765
♪♪

30:49.765 --> 30:52.851
♪♪

30:52.851 --> 30:54.352
He's dead.

30:54.352 --> 30:57.105
7‐Adam‐100, I have a 187
at the County Morgue.

30:57.105 --> 30:58.482
Suspect
is Chester Frey.

30:58.482 --> 30:59.941
Still outstanding
in the building.

30:59.941 --> 31:02.611
Have an RA stand by
until scene is secure.

31:02.611 --> 31:07.115
♪♪

31:07.115 --> 31:10.535
♪♪

31:10.535 --> 31:16.875
♪♪

31:16.875 --> 31:18.960
Chester:
Everyone, up against the wall.

31:20.587 --> 31:21.755
Go.

31:21.755 --> 31:23.590
[ Man whimpering ]

31:23.590 --> 31:26.218
Now! Faster!

31:26.218 --> 31:27.803
You ‐‐ Shut up.
Woman: [ Sobbing ] No.

31:27.803 --> 31:29.429
Shut up!
Help me!

31:29.429 --> 31:32.557
Stop crying!
Stop crying!

31:32.557 --> 31:35.143
Who's the guy in charge?
Raise your hand.

31:35.143 --> 31:36.812
Now!

31:36.812 --> 31:41.358
Okay, no one wants to raise
their hand?

31:41.358 --> 31:44.402
Should I start shooting?

31:44.402 --> 31:45.987
Good.

31:45.987 --> 31:48.740
You, come here.
I need his arm.

31:48.740 --> 31:51.576
That guy there,
on the table.

31:51.576 --> 31:54.830
Stop acting dumb.
You're in charge.

31:54.830 --> 31:56.790
You know how to use
these instruments.

31:56.790 --> 31:58.834
So go ahead.

31:58.834 --> 32:02.462
Pick it up. Start cutting.

32:02.462 --> 32:04.756
Why are you waiting?!

32:04.756 --> 32:06.758
It's either this arm
or your arm!

32:06.758 --> 32:07.926
So pick one!

32:07.926 --> 32:12.430
[ People whimpering ]

32:12.430 --> 32:15.183
Anyone moves, I'll blow
their head off. Do you hear me?

32:15.183 --> 32:17.102
It's him.
He's got hostages.

32:17.102 --> 32:20.522
[ Saw whirring ]
Faster.

32:20.522 --> 32:22.858
What are our options?
Faster!

32:22.858 --> 32:25.068
We could wait until
he gets what he wants

32:25.068 --> 32:27.028
and then flank him
on his way out,

32:27.028 --> 32:28.822
but he might kill the hostages
before he leaves.

32:28.822 --> 32:31.741
Which rules that out
as an option.

32:31.741 --> 32:34.828
We could make contact,
bring in a hostage negotiator,

32:34.828 --> 32:36.538
and try to talk him out.

32:36.538 --> 32:38.498
Given the video logs, do you
really think that's an option?

32:38.498 --> 32:41.001
No. Clearly, he thinks
he's on a divine mission.

32:41.001 --> 32:43.461
He'll probably shoot his way out
before he surrenders.

32:43.461 --> 32:47.132
So, what's our game plan?

32:47.132 --> 32:48.466
[ Breathing shakily ]

32:48.466 --> 32:49.759
Now the other one.

32:49.759 --> 32:51.970
♪♪

32:51.970 --> 32:53.555
[ Electricity crackles ]

32:53.555 --> 32:58.059
[ Heavy metal music plays ]

32:58.059 --> 33:01.438
[ Gunshots ]

33:01.438 --> 33:07.027
♪♪

33:07.027 --> 33:08.570
[ Taser clicking ]
[ Grunting ]

33:08.570 --> 33:15.410
♪♪

33:15.410 --> 33:17.412
7‐Adam‐100,
show a Code 4.

33:17.412 --> 33:18.872
Suspect in custody.

33:18.872 --> 33:20.373
[ Handcuffs click ]

33:20.373 --> 33:22.626
♪♪

33:22.626 --> 33:25.212
Okay, I put feelers out
through the union chat group ‐‐

33:25.212 --> 33:28.215
a great way to talk to every cop
in L. A., by the way ‐‐

33:28.215 --> 33:29.841
and between them all,
they have informants

33:29.841 --> 33:32.719
at 64 of the 71
no‐tell motels

33:32.719 --> 33:34.930
in the greater
Los Angeles area.

33:34.930 --> 33:39.059
Of those, one of them has
a possible Kai Zullo sighting.

33:39.059 --> 33:43.146
I say we go get into our civvies
and we stake it out.

33:44.648 --> 33:47.817
[ Voice breaking ] God,
I just love this job so much.

33:47.817 --> 33:50.111
[ Inhales,
exhales shakily ]

33:50.111 --> 33:52.822
Maybe I should drive.
Yeah. Okay.

33:52.822 --> 33:54.324
So you mentioned yesterday

33:54.324 --> 33:58.828
that you had
a bit of a history with Kai.

33:58.828 --> 34:00.455
<i>Si, si.</i>

34:00.455 --> 34:01.957
I arrested him
when I first started

34:01.957 --> 34:04.084
with the <i>Polizia Municipale</i>
<i>di Roma,</i>

34:04.084 --> 34:05.919
and many times since.

34:05.919 --> 34:09.047
He's a [chuckles] ‐‐
a repeat offender.

34:09.047 --> 34:10.590
Unh‐unh. There's something
about this case

34:10.590 --> 34:13.260
you're not telling me.

34:13.260 --> 34:16.554
I don't know, just...
seems personal.

34:16.554 --> 34:19.140
All my cases are personal.
[ Chuckles ]

34:19.140 --> 34:20.934
Are yours not?
Hmm.

34:20.934 --> 34:22.602
[ Cellphone ringing ]

34:22.602 --> 34:24.938
Excuse me.

34:24.938 --> 34:26.856
[ Exhales sharply ]

34:26.856 --> 34:28.191
Yeah?

34:28.191 --> 34:30.235
It's Nolan.
We got eyes on Kai.

34:30.235 --> 34:32.654
You want us to move in,
make the arrest?

34:32.654 --> 34:34.072
No, I have a better idea.

34:34.072 --> 34:35.365
[ Dramatic music plays ]

34:35.365 --> 34:38.326
[ Vehicle doors close ]

34:38.326 --> 34:39.661
He's in room 13.

34:39.661 --> 34:41.162
Harper's in
the manager's office,

34:41.162 --> 34:42.330
having the clerk call
all the rooms around,

34:42.330 --> 34:43.707
making sure
no one comes out.

34:43.707 --> 34:45.000
You wanna wait for SWAT?

34:45.000 --> 34:47.460
Yeah.
[ Chuckles ]
Like scared little children?

34:47.460 --> 34:50.088
No. Surely, we're men enough
to go arrest him.

34:50.088 --> 34:51.256
It's not about being "men,"
Romeo.

34:51.256 --> 34:52.799
It's about officer safety.

34:52.799 --> 34:55.468
But I do think
we can handle one armed felon.

34:55.468 --> 34:57.470
Somebody's gonna have to post up
in the alley, though,

34:57.470 --> 34:58.680
make sure
he doesn't rabbit.

34:58.680 --> 35:00.348
Allow me.

35:01.641 --> 35:03.101
Okay.

35:03.101 --> 35:05.812
Get in position.
We'll move in when you call.

35:05.812 --> 35:11.860
♪♪

35:11.860 --> 35:14.112
[ Baby crying ]

35:14.112 --> 35:19.701
♪♪

35:19.701 --> 35:25.332
♪♪

35:25.332 --> 35:29.336
[ Kai humming in Italian ]

35:29.336 --> 35:37.510
♪ <i>La giubba</i>
<i>e la faccia infarina</i> ♪

35:37.510 --> 35:41.056
♪ <i>La gente paga</i> ♪

35:41.056 --> 35:42.474
[ Gunshots ]
♪ <i>E rider</i> ♪

35:42.474 --> 35:46.853
♪ <i>Vuole qua</i> ♪

35:46.853 --> 35:50.482
♪ <i>E se Arlecchin</i> ♪

35:50.482 --> 35:52.233
Drop the gun, Romeo!

35:52.233 --> 36:02.243
♪♪

36:02.243 --> 36:03.411
[ Gun clatters ]

36:03.411 --> 36:05.372
[ Siren wails in distance ]

36:05.372 --> 36:08.291
Harper and Nolan
arrested Kai 20 minutes ago.

36:08.291 --> 36:11.002
He confessed to working with you
back in Italy,

36:11.002 --> 36:14.422
but then he killed a homeowner
and fled to America.

36:14.422 --> 36:18.093
And you worried he would
flip on you if he got caught,

36:18.093 --> 36:19.219
so you came to kill him.

36:19.219 --> 36:20.887
But what you didn't foresee

36:20.887 --> 36:24.307
is that you would get paired
with the best cop in the city.

36:24.307 --> 36:26.935
A man who believed in me

36:26.935 --> 36:28.561
when I didn't even
believe in myself.

36:28.561 --> 36:31.147
Seriously, how much longer you
gonna be like this?

36:31.147 --> 36:33.566
[ Sighs ]

36:33.566 --> 36:35.485
Let's go.
[ Sniffles ]

36:38.905 --> 36:40.949
Romeo on his way to
the Towers?

36:40.949 --> 36:44.577
Yeah, and, um,
Kai is on his way back to Italy

36:44.577 --> 36:46.663
with two U. S. Marshals.

36:46.663 --> 36:48.498
Thanks for everything
you did today.

36:48.498 --> 36:51.126
Of course. You okay?

36:51.126 --> 36:55.213
Yeah. It's just...

36:55.213 --> 36:56.506
I liked the guy.

36:56.506 --> 36:59.509
You liked
who he was pretending to be.

36:59.509 --> 37:02.220
Yeah.

37:02.220 --> 37:03.763
I'll see you tomorrow.

37:03.763 --> 37:06.141
Can't wait.
[ Chuckles ]

37:06.141 --> 37:10.103
[ "Brightside" plays ]

37:10.103 --> 37:12.897
Hey. Uh,
I wanted to talk to you.

37:12.897 --> 37:16.067
Have to be honest ‐‐ I‐I wasn't
really feeling last night,

37:16.067 --> 37:18.695
hanging with
Ashley and Tim.

37:18.695 --> 37:20.655
I am so sorry.

37:20.655 --> 37:22.866
Tim and I spend so much time
together on the jobs,

37:22.866 --> 37:24.784
we ‐‐
we have a shorthand.

37:24.784 --> 37:26.619
No, no, it's fine.

37:26.619 --> 37:28.538
I just don't think
our first date

37:28.538 --> 37:30.749
should've been
a double date.

37:32.000 --> 37:33.960
So, how about a do‐over?

37:33.960 --> 37:36.171
